  "answer": "**No poem in the Falsafa corpus matches this description.**\n\nI searched extensively using distinctive phrases from your query (\"hidden from his own gaze\", \"drinks the cup of twilight\", \"bitterness\" / \"bitter\" + \"existence\", \"riddle\" + \"gaze\", \"rivers\" + \"winds\", \"setting sun\", \"self-content\", \"riddle\", \"human existence\") across English translations, which yielded zero results for most and only unrelated \"riddle\" mentions in Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 1* (ch. 44) and Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-E-Ghalib* (ch. 44).[^1][^2]\n\nI also reviewed poetry works (*Old English Elegies*, Cynewulf's poems, Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara* parts, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, *Diwan-E-Zauq*) and read key elegies/chapters (*The Wanderer*, *Resignation*, *Soul and Body II*, *The Ruin*) for thematic fits (e.g., human sorrow contrasted with nature), but none frame humanity as a riddle hidden from self-gaze, contrast with self-content rivers/winds/stars/setting sun \"drinking twilight,\" or close with a shared-bitterness lament.[^3][^4][^5][^6][^7]\n\nThe corpus (38 works, focused on philosophy/classics) lacks this poem; it may be from another source or a different translation not present here.",
